```python
class Module:
    def parameters(self): return []
    def __call__(self, x): return self.forward(x)

class Linear(Module):
    def __init__(self, w, b): self.w=w; self.b=b
    def forward(self, x): return [sum(wi*xi for wi,xi in zip(row,x))+bi
                                  for row,bi in zip(self.w,self.b)]
    def parameters(self): return [self.w, self.b]

class Sequential(Module):
    def __init__(self, *layers): self.layers=layers
    def forward(self, x):
        for l in self.layers: x=l(x)
        return x
    def parameters(self): return [p for l in self.layers for p in l.parameters()]

net=Sequential(Linear([[1,0],[0,1]],[0,0]), Linear([[1,1]],[0]))
print(net([2,3]), len(net.parameters()))   # forward works; 4 param groups
```

The Module pattern is the organizing idea behind every framework: a uniform `forward` + `parameters` interface lets you nest layers arbitrarily and have the optimizer reach *all* parameters via one call. `nn.Module` and `nn.Sequential` are exactly this with more bells.
